 S_(3n) = 3n/2 (6 + 6n * 3 - 3).  Because we are told that
\begin{align*}
S_{3n} = CS_{n}
\end{align*}
for some constant $C,$ then we have 
    \begin{align*}
3n/2 * (18 + 18n) = C*(3n/2)((2 + 2n)*3 - 3)  \\
3n/2 (2 - 3 + 6n + 2n^2) = 3C * n/2(2 + 2n) \\
6n - 9 + 12n + 6n^2 = 3C(2 + 2n) \\
6n^2 + 18n - 9 = 3C(2 + 2n) \\
6n^2 + 18n - 9 = 6C + 6Cd
    \end{align*}
where $d$ is an arbitrarily specified variable
However, this doesn't lead me anywhere.  I know that $d$ must be zero or 1 for equality to hold as a constant.  But I can't figure out why.  Here's how I proceeded further:
Substitution gives $d = \pm \frac{\sqrt{13}}{3}$, and in the end I got
\begin{align*}
  C = \frac{9 - 6d^2-18d}{12d(d-1)}
\end{align*}
which doesn't look right to me.  When I try to plug in $n=1, 2, 3$ I get different values of $C$ and it seems I must be getting the values wrong.  Also, I'm assuming that my solution for $d$ is correct, since it is in a part of the question.


Assistant: The key to this question is $n$.  When we're adding $n-1$ terms of an arithmetic sequence, they don't sum to $2(n-1) + 1$.  We need to know the common difference.
It may seem mysterious that the common difference is $3$, but anytime we add the last term of an arithmetic sequence to the sums of the preceding $n-1$ terms we get the sum of the first $3n$ terms subtracting $1$ from our $n$ because we've subtracted one fewer for the sum of the preceding $n-1$ terms.  To see this, look the following picture.

For this picture, note that each piece of the green region larger than the white ones corresponds to two pieces of area in the left hand side square, while each piece of the white area corresponds to an area in the first square (green and white combine into a white square).  Why this should be clear is somewhat ad-hoc so for the moment we'll assume we know.  So since we are adding up $3n$ terms we multiply our scene by three and get that $S_{3n} = 9S_n$ and since $S_n$ is constant you find that we want $9C = C$.  However if the first term $y_1$ is nonzero and we know that $d = 3$ we can say that $$S_n = \frac{n}{2}(2y_1 + n - 1)(3)$$ $$S_{3n} = \frac{3n}{2}(6y_1 + 8n - 1)(3)$$ and $$\frac{S_{3n}}{S_n} = \frac{18y_1 + 24n^2 -3}{2y_1 + 2n^2 -n}$$ which doesn't break our assumptions as long as $S_n \neq 0$ for all $n$.
So the first term is $y_1 = \frac{-1}{2}$

