Now, $C = -(\tan A + \tan B),$ and $D = \tan A \tan B.$ </think>

Consequently, $\tan (A + B) = \dfrac{\tan A + \tan B}{1 - \tan A \tan B}.$

Meanwhile, using the identities $\sin (\alpha + \beta) = \sin \alpha \cos \beta + \cos \alpha \sin \beta,$ and $\cos ^2 \alpha + \sin ^2 \alpha = 1,$

\[\cos^2 (A + B) = \dfrac{1}{\cos^2 (A + B) + \sin^2 (A + B)} = \dfrac{1}{1 + \dfrac{\sin^2 (A + B)}{\cos^2 (A + B)}}.\]

Thus, $\cos^2 (A + B) =\dfrac{ 1}{1 + \dfrac{\sin^2 (A +B)}{\cos^2 (A + B)}}.$

So,
\begin{align*}
\sin^2 (A + B) + C \sin (A+B) \cos (A+B) + D \cos^2 (A + B)
&= \sin^2 (A + B) - (\tan A + \tan B) \sin (A + B) \cos (A+ B) + \tan A \tan B \cos^2 (A+B)
\\ &= \sin^2 (A + B) - \dfrac{\sin (A + B) \cos (A + B)(\sin A + \sin B)}{\cos^2 (A + B)}
\\ &= \sin^2 (A + B)\left(1 - \dfrac{\cos (A + B)}{\cos^2 (A + B)}\right) - \dfrac{\sin (A+B) \cos (A + B) (\sin A + \sin B)}{\cos^2 (A+B)}
\\ &= \sin^2 (A + B)\dfrac{\cos A \cos B - \sin A \sin B}{\cos^2 (A + B)} - \dfrac{\sin (A+B) \cos (A + B)(\sin A + \sin B)}{\cos^2 (A+B)}
\\ &= \dfrac{(\sin (A + B))(\sin A \cos B - \cos A \sin B + \cos A \sin B + \sin A \cos B)}{\cos^2 (A + B)}
\\ &= \dfrac{(\sin A + \sin B) (\sin A + \sin B)}{\cos^2 (A + B) }
\\ \implies \sin^2 (A + B) + C \sin (A + B) \cos (A + B) + D \cos^2 (A + B)
& = \tan^2 (A + B) = \boxed{C \tan (A + B) + D} \, .
\end{align*}

